passages.text: FY25 Result: Rebased International revenue expectations; positive progress on UK strategy - upside remains clear

PXA reported an FY25 result, which was a small miss vs our forecasts, led predominantly by a miss on International revenues. Looking forward into FY26, guidance appears to assume continued softness in the UK market, and very little in the way of incremental revenues from the Natwest partnership or progress in the cash- only market. This is despite what appears to be meaningful traction in engaging conveyancers, the imminent launch of the S&P product which would enable progress in the cash- only market and the recently announced Natwest partnership. New CEO Russell Cohen appears to be taking a more cautious approach to communication of timelines - noting further detail on progress would be provided at the 1H26 result. We see the following near- term catalysts: (1) Meaningful recruitment of conveyancers onto the platform (noting national roadshow next month); (2) Successful execution of Natwest partnership - due to go live in 2H26; and (3) Other Tier 1 bank partnerships. Each milestone would enable us to unwind our discount to valuation. We have adjusted Group Operating EBITDA in FY26/27 by \(- 14\% / - 20\%\) reflecting the removal of platform revenues in these years. We move to a \(\) 17.00\(PT and retain our OW noting near- term catalysts and upside to valuation.

- FY26 Guidance appears conservative: PEXA is guiding to FY26 revenue of \(\) 405-430\(nm, implying revenue growth of 2.9-9.2\% or 6.1\% at the midpoint. If we were to assume the FY25 ex-CPI revenue growth for PEXA Exchange (3.9\%) and adjust for the FY26 2.4\% CPI price increase (3.9\% + 2.4\% = 6.3\%), pro-forma ex-FX International revenue growth (11.1\%) and Digital Solutions revenue growth (21.7\%), we arrive at FY26 revenue growth of 7.8\% for the Group which would be towards the upper end of the 2.9-9.2\% guided range. This prima-facie appears achievable with no allowance for upside on FY25 trends.

- New CEO takes cautious approach to UK strategy: New CEO Russell Cohen has achieved tangible progress in the UK strategy, having secured the Natwest contract partnership. In today's update, Russell spoke of successfully engaging conveyancers (this is new) and plans to embark on a national roadshow across the UK as early as next month. The immediate focus in the UK appears to be: (1) successful/seamless execution on the Natwest partnership; (2) meeting with and signing conveyancers on to the platform. Whilst it is pleasing to see progress with conveyancers, who are key to the success of the strategy and had not been engaged prior to this update - very little detail has been provided on revenue/pricing models or the timing of when revenues would come on. We have downgraded FY26/27 international revenue expectations until further clarity is provided to the market.

PEXA is the operator of the largest digital property settlements platform (PEXA Exchange) in Australia. PEXA Exchange is involved in ~90% of all property transactions across Australia,and enjoys a monopolistic market position in e-conveyancing.We think there are limited near-term risks to this dominant market position, given ARNECC's announcement that it is pausing interpretability and standing down all project teams as well as Sympli's decision to move away from interoperability.PEXA is looking to replicate this success in the UK, and has recently achieved some key milestones which we think provide investors with incrementally improved confidence in PEXA's prospects for success in the UK. If PEXA is able to consistently deliver on its communicated milestones, we think the market will start placing value on its growth businesses.

Our 30 June 2026 price target of $17.00 is based on a ~5% discount to our SOTP valuation of $17.90 using a 16.2x EBITDA multiple for each business (i.e. look through short-term volatility in ASX multiple), based on applying a 12.5% discount to the longer-term 18x EV/EBITDA multiple to allow for PEXA's higher CAPEX/EBITDA ratio.

PXA is guiding to FY26 revenue of \(\) 405- 430\$ mn implying revenue growth of \(2.9 - 9.2\%\) revenue growth, or \(6.1\%\) at the midpoint. Of this, PEXA Exchange Australia has already locked in CPI- based increases of \(2.4\%\) for FY26, which alone contributes \(2\%\) to group revenue growth. Adjusting for this implies revenue growth of \(0.9 - 7.2\%\) which appears modest taking into consideration: (1) Falling interest rate environment should be supportive of growth in transfer volumes and refis in Australia; (2) Gov policy surrounding first home buyer support should be supportive of transfer volumes. If we were to assume the FY25 ex- CPI revenue growth for PEXA Exchange and adjust for the FY26 \(2.4\%\) CPI price increase \((3.9\% +2.4\% = 6.3\%)\) pro- forma ex- FX International revenue growth \((11.1\%)\) and Digital Solutions revenue growth \((21.7\%)\) , we arrive at FY26 revenue growth of \(7.8\%\) for the Group which would be towards the upper end of the \(2.9 - 9.2\%\) guided range. This prima- facie appears achievable with no allowance for upside to FY25 trends.

PXA's recent Natwest contract win was a key catalyst for the stock, as the market saw it as evidence of tangible progress in their UK strategy. Today, we learnt PXA have engaged with conveyancers and are in the process of beta testing the platform. They will also be embarking on a national roadshow across the UK as early as next month, with a focus on meeting with and signing on conveyancers. They also noted using the cash only market as a test case to demonstrate functionality to conveyancers. Unfortunately, details remain scarce, with the following questions unanswered: (1) the number of conveyancers engaged so far; (2) the revenue model adopted with conveyancers, noting conveyancers would likely be losing interest income on cash balances held in trust which are a material contributor to their revenues; and (3) timing of when we would likely see revenues.

We do note however, that getting conveyancers on board is key to the UK strategy so it is pleasing to see progress. Management appear to be taking a more cautious approach in communicating progress, indicating further detail to be provided at the next result.

International - efficiency uplifts offset soft macro backdropInternational saw pro- forma revenue growth of \(11.1\%\) (assuming full year contribution of Smoove in FY24 and adjusting out FX benefits). Management commented that market volumes remained depressed, with refinance volumes in particular remaining at all- time lows, in a tough macroeconomic backdrop. Management appear to be assuming that these pressures persist into FY25. They noted the following points: (1) Smoove was able to achieve break even in 2H25; (2) Significant progress in Optima Legal operational efficiencies, leading to reducing losses; (3) Optima Legal saw market share gains, growing completion by \(8.5\%\) in a market which declined \(8\%\) on FY24; (4) \(10.4\mathrm{mm}\) of total productivity and \(54\mathrm{mm}\) from actions taken in FY25 to have run- rate benefits into FY26.

Cash flow profile improving; reduced gearing to further support this outlookPXA reported notable improvements in its free cash flow profile for FY25 at \(\) 56\mathrm{mm}\(vs\) \ \(38.5\mathrm{mm}\) vs ppb but flat trends in 2H vs 1H at \(\sim\) \(\) 28\mathrm{mm}\(. FCF conversion rate improved to\) 45.8\%\$ in FY25 vs \(39.9\%\) in FY24 and improved in 2H as 1H25 was at \(40.4\%\) . This reflects some seasonality in property transactions that are slightly skewed to 1H, leading to slightly lower adjusted EBITDA in 2H. Net debt / EBITDA improved to \(1.8x\) by FY25 end from \(2.5x\) in FY24 end and only very slightly from \(1.9x\) from 1H25 end, reflecting substantial debt reduction of \(\sim\) \(\) 55\mathrm{mm}\(in 1H25, while improvement in 2H gearing reflects slightly better net- debt position from higher cash position. CAPEX spend was broadly stable in 2H25 at\) \ \(29.4\mathrm{mm}\) vs \(\) 28.4\mathrm{mm}\$ in 1H25 but slowed vs FY24 at \(\) 68.8\mathrm{mm}\$. This is however guided at \(\) 60- \(\) 65\mathrm{mm}\$ levels for FY26, to support business resilience through cybersecurity enhancements, platform modernization, and reflecting ongoing integration expense supporting growth prospects in both domestic and international markets.

- JPM key takeaways: The FY25 result was a small headline miss on our numbers at the Operating EBITDA line - but was a beat at the underlying NPAT/NPATA line due to changes in the treatment of tax on significant items. Revenues came in slightly behind our forecasts, driven by a miss on International with both PEXA Exchange and Digital Solutions both broadly coming in line. Guidance into FY26 on revenues appears weak at just \(5.5\%\) at the midpoint - but this perhaps is based on

soft expectations on macro outcomes in the coming 12 months. They have noted progress in the UK noting engagement with conveyancers - but have not provided updates on large banks noting "commercial in confidence".

- PXA for FY25 reported: 1) Group Operating EBITDA of \(136.7mn\) (JPMF \(137.5mn\) ) led by EBITDA from Business Revenue of \(395.9mn\) (JPMF \(399.1mn\) ), 2) Operating Expense - \(192.5mn\) (JPMF - \(191.4mn\) ), 3) Group NPAT of - \(76.1mn\) (JPMF - \(81.4mn\) ), and 4) Group NPATA - \(37.1mn\) (JPMF - \(39.5mn\) ).

- Key positives: (1) Progress in International appears to be tracking well: (a) On track for S&P platform launch in 1H26 as guided, with test transactions successfully completed. "Launch of PEXA UK platform imminent"; (b) Natwest formal agreement (known); (c) Completion of Smoove integration with 2H25 breakeven achieved; (d) Beta testing with select conveyancers indicating solid progress on this key topic; (e) Noting progress on the Tier 1 bank is "commercial in confidence" - does this imply progress? (2) Free cashflow has improved materially on FY24. (3) PEXA Exchange now live in Tasmania and launch is imminent in NT - with expansion of capabilities in WA.

- Key negatives: (1) PXA International revenues were below JPM expectations. (2) Transfer volumes in Australia softer than expected for 2H, impacted by election and weather. Refinance strength led to an unfavorable mix shift. (3) International revenues came in weaker than expected in 2H, driven by weaker transaction volumes in remo and S&P. (4) Softer transaction volumes in PEXA Exchange in 2H led to softer EBITDA margins for the Exchange and the Group. (5) No material progress with Tier 2 and Tier 3 lenders, and disclosure on Tier 1 lenders has been removed citing "commercial in confidence". (6) Revenue growth for FY26 is guided to just 5.5% at the midpoint.

PEXA (Overweight; Price Target: A\(17.00)

PEXA is the operator of the largest digital property settlements platform (PEXA Exchange) in Australia. PEXA Exchange is involved in \(\sim 90\%\) of all property transactions across Australia, and enjoys a monopolistic market position in e- conveyancing. We think there are limited near- term risks to this dominant market position, given ARNECC's announcement that it is pausing interpretability and standing down all project teams as well as Sympli's decision to move away from interoperability. PEXA is looking to replicate this success in the UK, and has recently achieved some key milestones which we think provide investors with incrementally improved confidence in PEXA's prospects for success in the UK. If PEXA is able to consistently deliver on its communicated milestones, we think the market will start placing value on its growth businesses.

Our 30 June 2026 price target is \(17.00 based on a \sim 5\%\) discount to our SOTP valuation of A\(17.90. Our SoTP valuation adopts an ASX- type EV/EBITDA multiple adjusted for differences in CAPEX/EBITDA ratios (reflected in a \sim 12.5\% discount). We look through short- term fluctuations in the ASX multiple for this purpose, and adopt a longer- term 18x EV/EBITDA multiple before applying our 12.5\% discount to arrive at our 16.2x valuation multiple for PEXA. For the International business, we assume a 75\% probability of success for 20\% market share at 35\% EBITDA margins. We ascribe a value to the Digital solutions business given positive FY25 EBITDA expectations, but apply the same multiple as the other businesses given uncertainties in growth going forward. We separately allow for\)50mn in expected additional CAPEX for the growth businesses.
